  "level_num": "custom",
  "user_id": 16889,
  "properties": {
    "encrypted": "false",
    "long_instructions": "The <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">ParkPainter</code> class declares instance variables for a 1D array of <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">String</code> values that stores the paint colors a <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">ParkPainter</code> object can paint with.\r\n\r\n✅ **TO DO #1:** In <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">ParkPainter.java</code>, update the <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">paintPark()</code> method to paint a line alternating between consecutive pairs of colors in the 1D array <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">paintColors</code>, then turn left. The <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">paintPark()</code> method should:\r\n\r\n1. Traverse the 1D array <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">paintColors</code> using a <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">for</code> loop, stopping at the second-to-last element.\r\n\r\n2. Call the <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">paintLine()</code> method to paint a line, alternating between the current color and the next color in the array.\r\n\r\n3. Turn left after painting the line.\r\n\r\n✅ **TO DO #2:** In <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">NeighborhoodRunner.java</code>,\r\n\r\nInstantiate a <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">ParkPainter</code> object at <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">(1, 9)</code>, facing <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">\"East\"</code>, with <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">40</code> units of paint.\r\n\r\nDeclare and initialize a 1D array of five paint colors.\r\n\r\nCall the <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">paintPark()</code> method.\r\n\r\n<div style=\"background-color: #E0D1EC; border: 1px solid #9660bf; border-radius: 5px; font-size: 1.1em; padding: 15px; margin-bottom: 10px;\">\r\n💡 <strong>TIP:</strong> Check out the <strong>Help & Tips</strong> tab ⬆️ for help with traversing a 1D array with a <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">for</code> loop.\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<details style=\"background-color: #ececec; padding: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px; border: 1px solid transparent; border-radius: 5px;\">\r\n    <summary style=\"font-size: 1.2em; font-weight: bold;\">🔦 Need help with your algorithm?</summary>\r\n    <div style=\"margin-top: 20px; margin-left: 20px; margin-right: 20px;\">\r\n    \t<p>Here is one approach to solving this problem.</p>\r\n        <pre style=\"background-color: #333333; color: white;\">\r\nfor each index in paintColors (except the last one)\r\n  firstColor = paintColors[index]\r\n  secondColor = paintColors[index + 1]\r\n  paintLine(firstColor, secondColor)\r\n  turn left\r\n</pre>\r\n    </div>\r\n</details>\r\n\r\n## ***Don't forget to . . .***\r\n\r\n![](https://images.code.org/eb2c8910ae2e150019b8e2177405d4af-image-1668191576873.png)\r\n\r\n## 🎯 Goal\r\n\r\n![](https://images.code.org/e51c0a852c4212022fea4c8d146a59a2-ezgif-20419afd5396fb.gif)",
    "mini_rubric": "false",
